[## LECTURE 6.1 — MULTI-AZ ARCHITECTURE: ELIMINATING SINGLE POINTS OF FAILURE]

1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Your application is secure. Your secrets are vaulted.
Your logs are immutable. But what happens when
an entire AWS Availability Zone goes down?

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Not a single server. The whole data center.
If you are running in one AZ, your system is down.
Your ninety-nine point nine percent SLO is blown.

3
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Your customers are angry.
That is the reality of single points of failure.
For SOC 2's availability criteria, CC7.1,
you need to prove your system can survive infrastructure failures.

4
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Hi there, and welcome to Phase 6 of our SOC 2 journey.
In this phase, we are building a highly available system
that can survive AZ failures, node failures, and even regional issues.

5
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
We will cover Multi-AZ RDS, EKS distribution across availability zones,
Redis persistence, HPA with Karpenter, PodDisruptionBudgets,
chaos engineering, and SLO monitoring.

6
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
By the end of these two hours, your system will have eliminated
single points of failure and proven its resilience
through automated chaos testing.

7
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Let me start with the foundation. Multi-AZ architecture.

8
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
The most critical component in our stack is the database.
If PostgreSQL goes down, everything stops.
RDS Multi-AZ creates a synchronous replica in another availability zone.

9
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
When the primary fails, AWS automatically fails over to the standby.
Usually in under two minutes.

10
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Create a verification script called verify-multi-az dot sh.
First, check RDS Multi-AZ status.

11
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
aws rds describe-db-instances for financial-rag-prod.
Query MultiAZ, AvailabilityZone, and SecondaryAvailabilityZone.
Output to JSON and save in the evidence directory.

12
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
If MultiAZ is true, RDS can survive an AZ failure.
If it is false, you have a single point of failure.

13
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Now check EKS node distribution across AZs.
kubectl get nodes and extract the topology dot kubernetes dot io forward slash zone label.
Count how many nodes are in each zone.

14
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
For high availability, you want nodes spread across three AZs.
If one AZ fails, the other two AZs continue serving traffic.

15
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Now check API pod distribution.
kubectl get pods with the component label set to api.
Verify that pods are running and count them.

16
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Save both outputs as evidence.
EKS node distribution and API pod distribution.

17
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Now enforce pod distribution across AZs with topology spread constraints.
In your API deployment YAML, add topologySpreadConstraints.

18
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
First constraint. maxSkew equals one.
topologyKey equals topology dot kubernetes dot io forward slash zone.
whenUnsatisfiable equals DoNotSchedule.

19
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
This means the scheduler will try to keep the number of pods
in each AZ equal. The allowed difference is at most one pod.
If it cannot schedule because of this constraint, it will not schedule the pod.

20
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Second constraint. Spread across nodes within each AZ.
maxSkew equals one. topologyKey equals kubernetes dot io forward slash hostname.
whenUnsatisfiable equals ScheduleAnyway.

21
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:30,000
This is a soft constraint. It prefers spreading pods across nodes
but will schedule even if it cannot.

22
00:10:30,000 --> 00:11:00,000
Also add podAntiAffinity.
preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution with weight one hundred.
This prevents two API pods from landing on the same node if possible.

23
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:30,000
Your lab exercise is to verify your RDS instance is Multi-AZ enabled.
Check node distribution across availability zones.
Deploy pods with topology spread constraints.

24
00:11:30,000 --> 00:12:00,000
Verify they are evenly distributed.
Simulate an AZ failure by cordoning all nodes in one AZ.
Verify pods reschedule elsewhere.

25
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:30,000
In the next lecture, we will configure HPA with custom metrics.
And Karpenter for node autoscaling.


