[## LECTURE 6.2 — HPA WITH CUSTOM METRICS]

26
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Multi-AZ gives you resilience.
But what about scale? On Black Friday, your traffic might spike ten times.
Without autoscaling, you either over-provision or under-provision.

27
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Over-provisioning is expensive.
Under-provisioning causes downtime.
You need two layers of autoscaling.

28
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Horizontal Pod Autoscaler scales the number of pods.
Based on CPU, memory, or custom metrics.
Karpenter scales the number of nodes when pods cannot schedule.

29
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Let me show you how to configure HPA with custom metrics.
First, install KEDA, the Kubernetes Event-Driven Autoscaler.

30
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
KEDA extends the HPA with more triggers.
Prometheus, SQS, Kafka, and many others.
helm repo add kedacore and helm install keda.

31
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Now create a ScaledObject for the API service.

32
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
scaleTargetRef points to the API deployment.
minReplicaCount is three. maxReplicaCount is twenty.

33
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
In the advanced section, configure HPA behavior.
scaleUp has stabilizationWindowSeconds zero.
Scale immediately when the metric threshold is crossed.

34
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
scaleUp policies include Percent with value one hundred.
And Pods with value four.
selectPolicy is Max. It chooses the policy that adds more replicas faster.

35
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
scaleDown has stabilizationWindowSeconds three hundred.
Wait five minutes before scaling down.
scaleDown policies include Percent with value ten.

36
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Now add the triggers.
First trigger. Prometheus metric. rag_http_requests_per_second.
Query is sum of rate of rag_queries_total over two minutes.
Threshold is one hundred requests per second.

37
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Second trigger. Prometheus metric. rag_p95_latency_ms.
Query is histogram quantile of latency buckets over two minutes.
Multiply by one thousand to get milliseconds.
Threshold is two thousand milliseconds. Two seconds.

38
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Third trigger. CPU utilization.
metricType is Utilization.
value is seventy percent.

39
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Now verify the HPA is configured correctly.
kubectl get hpa and kubectl get scaledobject.
Save both outputs as JSON and YAML evidence.

40
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Test the autoscaling with a load test.
Install hey for load testing.
Run hey for five minutes with one hundred concurrent connections.

41
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Watch the HPA scale.
kubectl get hpa minus n financial-rag minus w.
You should see replicas increase from three to ten or more.

42
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Watch Karpenter provision nodes.
kubectl logs minus n karpenter deployment forward slash karpenter minus f.
You will see logs like launched c5 dot xlarge and pods added.

43
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
After the load test, verify the system scales back down.
It may take several minutes because of the scaleDown stabilization window.

44
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Your lab exercise is to install KEDA.
Create a ScaledObject with Prometheus and CPU triggers.
Run a load test and watch the HPA scale.

45
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Document the time from load increase to new pods serving traffic.
In the next lecture, we will configure PodDisruptionBudgets.
To guarantee availability during maintenance.


