[## LECTURE 6.3 — PODDISRUPTIONBUDGETS: GUARANTEED AVAILABILITY DURING MAINTENANCE]

46
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Autoscaling handles traffic spikes.
But what about maintenance? When you need to update Kubernetes nodes,
they get drained. Pods are evicted and rescheduled.

47
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Without safeguards, this could take down all your replicas at once.
PodDisruptionBudgets ensure a minimum number of pods
remain running during voluntary disruptions.

48
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Create PDBs for every critical component.
First, for the API service.

49
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
apiVersion policy forward slash v1. kind PodDisruptionBudget.
metadata name financial-rag-agent-api.
spec minAvailable two. selector matches app dot kubernetes dot io forward slash component api.

50
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
This means at least two API pods must remain running.
Even during node drains or cluster upgrades.

51
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Second, for the agent service.
maxUnavailable one. selector matches component agent.
Only one agent pod can be disrupted at a time.

52
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Third, for Redis.
minAvailable one. selector matches component redis.
Redis is stateful. It must keep at least one pod running.

53
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Fourth, for Vault.
maxUnavailable one. selector matches app dot kubernetes dot io forward slash name vault.
Vault requires a quorum. Disrupting too many pods at once could cause unsealing issues.

54
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Apply the PDBs.
kubectl apply dash f.
Verify they are created. kubectl get pdb minus n financial-rag.

55
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Now test what happens when we try to drain a node.
Find a node that has API pods.
kubectl get pods minus n financial-rag dash o wide.

56
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Try to drain that node with dry-run.
kubectl drain with ignore-daemonsets and delete-emptydir-data.
If there are only two API pods, the drain will be blocked.

57
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
The error message says: cannot drain node because PodDisruptionBudget
requires at least two pods.

58
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
If you have spare replicas, the drain will proceed.
The PDB allows disruptions as long as the minimum is maintained.
Set up alerts for when PDB blocks evictions.

59
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Create a PrometheusRule for pdb-alerts.
Alert PDBNearViolation when current healthy pods
are less than desired healthy pods.

60
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Your lab exercise is to simulate node failure.
Cordon and drain a node. Verify the PDB blocks the drain
if it would violate availability.

61
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Test that you can still drain nodes when there are spare replicas.
In the next lecture, we will run chaos experiments.
To prove recovery, not just design.


