[## LECTURE 6.4 — CHAOS ENGINEERING: PROVE RECOVERY, NOT JUST DESIGN]

62
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
You have built a highly available system.
But does it actually work when things fail?
The only way to know is to break things on purpose.

63
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Chaos engineering is the practice of running experiments
that inject failures into your system to verify resilience.
LitmusChaos provides a framework for this.

64
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
First, install LitmusChaos.
kubectl apply dash f the Litmus operator manifest.
Wait for all pods to be ready.

65
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Now create a pod delete chaos experiment.

66
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
apiVersion litmuschaos dot io forward slash v1alpha1.
kind ChaosEngine.
metadata name financial-rag-api-pod-delete.
namespace financial-rag.

67
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
spec appinfo points to the API deployment.
chaosServiceAccount is litmus-admin.
experiments includes pod-delete.

68
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Under pod-delete spec, set PODS_AFFECTED_PERC to thirty-three.
TOTAL_CHAOS_DURATION to sixty seconds.
CHAOS_INTERVAL to fifteen seconds.

69
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Add a probe to verify the API stays healthy during chaos.
type httpProbe. url is the health endpoint.
responseCode must be two hundred.

70
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
mode is Continuous. probeTimeout five seconds.
interval two seconds. attempt five times.

71
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Apply the chaos engine.
kubectl apply dash f.
Monitor the experiment. watch kubectl get pods minus n financial-rag.

72
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
You will see pods being deleted every fifteen seconds.
The HPA should recreate them immediately.
After about two minutes, check the verdict.

73
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
kubectl get chaosresult.
The verdict should be Pass.
Save the chaos result as JSON evidence.

74
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Now simulate an AZ failure.
This is more destructive. Run it in staging first.

75
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Pick an AZ to fail, like us-east-1a.
Get all nodes in that AZ.
kubectl get nodes with the zone label.

76
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Cordon the nodes. This marks them as unschedulable.
Then drain the nodes. This evicts all pods.

77
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Start a timer.
Monitor the API pods until they are running again.
When the desired number of replicas is reached, stop the timer.

78
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
The recovery time is the difference between start and end.
For SOC 2 CC7.1, you should recover within two minutes.
Uncordon the nodes after the test.

79
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Save the simulation results as JSON.
Include the AZ simulated, nodes cordoned, recovery seconds, RTO target, and pass or fail.

80
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Your lab exercise is to run a pod delete chaos experiment.
Verify HPA recreates the pods.
Run an AZ failure simulation in staging.

81
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Document the recovery time for each experiment.
In the next lecture, we will run quarterly restore tests.
And measure RTO.


