[## LECTURE 6.7 — INCIDENT RESPONSE EVIDENCE]

112
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Availability monitoring tells you when something is wrong.
But what happens next? Your auditor needs evidence
that you have a process for responding to incidents.

113
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
First, document your on-call schedule.
Create a ConfigMap called oncall-schedule in the monitoring namespace.

114
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
The schedule includes the policy. 24x7 engineering on-call.
Primary escalation minutes. Five.
Secondary escalation minutes. Fifteen.

115
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
List the services. financial-rag-api.
PagerDuty service ID. Slack channel hash incidents.
SLA minutes for P1, P2, and P3.

116
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
List the team members and rotation schedule.
Weekly rotation. Engineer one, engineer two, engineer three.

117
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Now create a post-incident review generator.
A script that creates a markdown document with the standard template.

118
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
The template includes a timeline table.
Time, event, who acknowledged, what was done.
Root cause section. Corrective actions table.

119
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
SLA compliance section. Response time and whether it was within SLA.
Upload the PIR to the immutable evidence bucket.

120
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Run this script after any incident.
Even if the incident did not cause customer-facing downtime.
Documenting near misses shows a mature incident response process.

121
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Your lab exercise is to create the on-call schedule ConfigMap.
Create the post-incident review generator script.
Simulate a minor incident and generate a PIR.

122
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Upload the PIR to the evidence bucket.
In the final lecture of Phase 6, we will assemble the complete availability evidence package.


